# Logical Fallacies and the SCADA Problem

*Read the full story [here](https://craigwright.net/blog/economics/logical-fallacies-and-the-scada-problem/).*

The arguments for extreme events are interesting, and one has to wonder about the motivation for them. The argument that a “[**STUXPOCALYPSE**](https://web.archive.org/web/20151123164858/https://www.infosecisland.com/blogview/17371-Stuxnet-SCADA-Nation-State-Terrorism-and-FUD.html)” will not occur and hence we need not worry about the security of critical systems is astounding.

**Straw Man**

The first logical flaw is an argument based on the misrepresentation of an opponent’s position.

The argument is not one of apocalypse, it is one of widespread damage. Here, 100 deaths and a few million dollars are considered widespread damage. It is quantitatively different from the end of the world. The point is not whether an attack against Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition (SCADA) will result in the end of civilisation as we know it. Even World War II did not manage to do so with all the damage it created, and a SCADA cascade will not do something as dire.

![][image_ref_MSpGTjNLTlZvNmVSb2htcTVYbjlfbTNnLmpwZWc=]

So one has to wonder what the motivations and imperatives are for those who attempt to downplay the security concerns surrounding unsecured control systems.

Using [rhetorical tricks](https://web.archive.org/web/20151123164858/https://www.infosecisland.com/blogview/17371-Stuxnet-SCADA-Nation-State-Terrorism-and-FUD.html) in order to mask the concerns around the security of control systems and to downplay the nature of such threats smells a little fishy.
